english:
  title: Inscription on the Scroll of Four Verses on Orchid Slope
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When I dwelt in Pine Capital, I visited my teacher's study daily. To left and right, no other things were present—only zither and books lay beside the desk. A small basin stood nearby, wherein he had planted pine, bamboo, plum, and orchid, which he would contemplate and find joy in.

    I reflect thus: common people, in their regard for pine and bamboo, plum and orchid, perceive only their verdant hue, their lustrous flourishing. Do any truly know that their subtle wonder communes with the heart?

    When frost and snow veil the heavens and summer's blazing clouds ignite the sky, those dense pines and bamboos stand solitary and resolute—this is where Yang virtue concentrates. When ice-clad cliffs crack and all flowers fade from sight, plum blossoms alone emerge, pure and fragrant—thus springs the fullness of spring's spirit. At dawn with its dew and dusk with its moonlight, their fragrance turns cool and piercing to the nose. This is the orchid's nature: it draws deeply of Yang's breath, and its subtle perfume—ah, it rivals the virtue of the noble man.

    Yang qi, when traced to its source, communes with heaven and earth's generative principle. Though plants are humble, their vital force and growth flow uninterrupted with this mind's own generative nature. Thus does my teacher find joy—he has grasped this truth. He tends these plants with devoted care and diligent cultivation. How much more then for people, who share our kind and are supremely precious? How much more for those of kindred spirit and harmonious qi, like clouds that follow the dragon?

    Now, as I take up the post of Inspector in Gyeongsang Province, I shall extend this heart outward. I shall lead these people toward the joy inherent in their very existence, so that they flourish as plants flourish beneath timely rain. Of this, I have no doubt.
  footnotes:
    - Pine Capital (松京) refers to Kaesong, the capital of Goryeo.
    - The four plants—pine, bamboo, plum, and orchid—are classical symbols in East Asian aesthetics representing resilience, integrity, beauty, and virtue respectively.
    - Yang (陽) here carries both cosmological and moral significance, representing the dynamic, generative principle of the universe.
    - The final image of clouds following the dragon alludes to natural harmony and the ideal relationship between ruler and people.
